<br>
1) Druids actually do quite well with these.  Just myself and a druid played Nukers in D2 for hours, handling 12+ mob pulls just fine.  We just used my pet and a tank wrap up the Ilis spawns.  (I was 58, the druid was 53)  Upheaval works fine.<br>
<br>
2) Clerics do well as AEers.  I've handled the bar/chef area with 2 clerics, myself, druid, paladin, and ench.<br>
<br>
3) Clerics make great lead rushers.  When doing the technique described above where you all rush to where you want to fight, we use a cleric with DA up to go ahead of us a few seconds.  Everything agros him and we follow him in, then stop and AE.<br>
<br>
4) Shaman can be useful to slow and do quick heals.  We frequently do pulls of 4 mobs at a time to be mez'ed, the shaman slows, then we send out the puller to bring 4+ mobs.  Having half of them slowed eases up the hitting.<br>
<br>
5) AE tash makes a great lead off spell.  Our enchanter will throw this out, and I time my scintilation to get the mobs attention.  This makes following AE stuns go much smoother.  AE tash also has a nice low taunt compared to regular tash.<br>
<br>
6) Any group I'm in with an evacer is an AE group.  Any trains we get, in almost any zone is handled by AE.  My enchanter friend is always with me, so it's just something we do.<br>
<br>
7) Explain the rules up front to everyone.  Make sure everyone knows their role, and who to follow.<br>
<br>
The last 3 months playing EQ was done almost completely in AE groups, or at least, partial AE groups.  The extra excitement that AE brings is so much more fun than the standard grouping and nothing brings a bigger smile than to see new members reactions the first time they do it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usampox.showPublicProfile?language=EN>sampox</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_bluespot.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 96<br> <font color=#333333>(5/15/01 2:01:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  if you add in flame arc</span><hr size=1> tossing in flame arc right after scintillation gives an extra 181 damage and overlaps scint by only 1.5 seconds...which means that even with an interrupt you wouldnt be that far behind if you hadnt cast it...always worth loading up in my opinion. the previous level 24 spell however is not worthwhile with cast time of 7 seconds and damage of 98.<br>
